		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11341'>cutie</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">Well written.  Good read, decent summary of ideas.  Ok now for the "disagreement" stuff.  I found it quite interesting that you only chose defensive approaches to +1 damage, healing and site location.  Other ways to preven +1 damage is to win the skirmishes, or cancel skirmishes.  Yet this didn&#39;t make it as some of your preventative techniques.  This is how decks that don&#39;t have access to armor can deal with +1 damage ie. hobbit stealth, gandy&#39;s staff, etc.  Healing, again you only took the defensive stand as in have some, well if you win skirmishes, or prevent skirmishes you prevent the wounds.  Hence less healing.  For location control, lag behind and it&#39;s your sites that get played so hence you have control.  You covered condition removal well, and I do believe it is quite important, but you can win games without condition removal it&#39;s just easier if you have it.  I found it funny that you shot down removing condition during the maneuver phase !?! that&#39;s the best phase to do it.  The shadow just played out a bunch of conditions you can now remove them.  Now this is just what I didn&#39;t agree with, but you did write a lot that I did agree with.  I don&#39;t agree with your archery and denial beliefs but whatever, it&#39;s your belief.<br>
