Glyph  <font size=1>(+2 tp)</font><BR>
		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1625'>UnknownGlyph</a></font> <font class="afont">( was very helpful )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">This is a very nice article, but I disagree with several things.  One, twilight denial is MUCH more important than you seem to think.  I&#39;m guessing you&#39;ve never even played Moria, you downplayed how important twilight is to them.  Have you ever seen the card Goblin Swarms?  It can often get 10+ guys on it (unless you&#39;ve dealt with the condition removal part of your deck :)), and most of those usually just sit there.  Just hand out free twilight, and you&#39;re gonna get swarmed to hell and back.  Ancient Chieftain? Guard Commander? Also, it&#39;s INCREDIBLY useful for any amount of twilight in any of the other decks.  Nazgul usually only play a guy or two because of their high costs, but give them enough twilight, and you could be swarmed by Nazgul :/.  They can get out all their big guys, weapons, and use powerful events in the same turn, which is asking to be killed.  Uruk-hai- same thing.  Hunt Them Down is one of the more useful cards in the game, but its high cost makes it less useful (and Uruk Rampage).  If they&#39;ve got a bunch of extra twilight, you&#39;re gonna have several fierce dmg +1 guys coming at you.  And for Sauron, lots of twilight = 1) easy getting out of Orc Bowmen, 2) Possible Swarm, 3) Many of their high costing guys getting easily out.  Also, you don&#39;t use Sting and Glamdring for their abilities!?!  While the twilight removal may not seem to useful to you, looking at an opponent&#39;s hand is crucial.  You can see exactly how much twilight they need to be effective, (and choose what and what not to play), and you can decide whether the double move is worth it.  The strength bonus is also very useful :).  Now what do  you have against discarding conditions during the Maneuver?  That&#39;s even better as they&#39;ve just layed down any conditions they may have.  And, you don&#39;t think very hightly of Secret Sentinels, while it may be even better than Sleep.  Just have it used against you 3 times in a game with a Moria deck, and you&#39;ll see.  I  agree with you for the most part on the Archery part.  Don&#39;t get me wrong though- this is a very good, well written article that is very useful for newer players, and still good for older ones.  You encouraged disagreement after all :).  However, it sort of got repetitive after a while, but overall very nice job.  <font size=1>(+2 tp)</font><BR>
